info.name: Work Queue Integration
info.description: This collection provides a set of pre-built API requests for interacting with work queues in Dataverse. With these requests, you can easily create, update, and delete work queues, as well as add and process items from them.

body.raw:
{
    "workqueuetype": 0,
    "name": "AAA My Work Queue Test",
    "description": "AAA My queue with a 14 day SLA.",
    "workqueuekey": "AAA My Work Queue Test",
    "prioritytype": 0,
    "defaultitemtimetoliveinminutes": 20160
}

exec: pm.test("Set New Work Queue Item Id", function () {
This JavaScript script generates a batch of work queue items (WQIs) for a fictitious invoicing system.
1. The script generates a specified number of work queue items for an invoicing system.
2. Creates unique invoice IDs and dates for each work queue item.
3. Sets up a list of account names and maps them to their corresponding domain names.
4. Generates contact emails for each account using the domain map.
5. Generates random invoice amounts for each work queue item.
6. Defines possible statuses for the invoices.
7. Creates each WQI by selecting random account names, contact emails, amounts, and statuses.
8. Creates a batch request body with the array of work queue items and sets it as the value for the "payload" variable in the request body.
// Define the number of workqueueitems you want to create
const invoiceIds = Array.from({ length: numWQI }, (_, i) => {
const dates = Array.from({ length: numWQI }, (_, i) => {
// Object to map account names to domains
const amounts = Array.from({ length: numWQI }, () => Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000) + 1000);
// Optional: Add 1 day to the current date as expiry if there is no default TTL specified
//Uncomment if you want to set specific expiry dates
// Push the workqueueitem object to the workqueueitem array
// Set the batch request body as the value for the "payload" variable in the request body
// Check if the status code is in the 2xx range (indicating success)
pm.expect(true).to.be.true; // Assertion for passing the test
pm.expect.fail('POST request failed with status code: ' + pm.response.code);
